    <div class=3D"faq-block__card faq-generic">
                        <h2 class=3D"card-header">
            Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs) About Bandwidth Calculator
          </h2>
                    <div class=3D"faq-block__card-block">
                          <ul class=3D"faq-block__list list-unstyled">
                          <li class=3D"faq-block__list-item embed-faq__item=
" data-toggle=3D"collapsed">
                <h2 class=3D"faq-block__question">What Does Mbps Mean?</h2>
                <i class=3D"faq-block__arrow down"></i>
                <div class=3D"faq-block__answer collapsed"><p>Megabits per =
second (Mbps) is the most common measurement of consumer-grade Internet con=
nections. It=E2=80=99s not important to understand what a =E2=80=9Cbit=E2=
=80=9D is, so long as you=E2=80=99re familiar with the range of speeds on t=
he market.</p>
<p>Internet plans can be anywhere from 1 Mbps all the way up 1,000 Mbps or =
more. Anything above 25 Mbps is considered usable for modern applications. =
Speeds below 200 Mbps can be challenging for a large household. Use the too=
l above to calculate what speed range you should be looking for when shoppi=
ng for Internet service.</p>
</div>
                              </li>
                          <li class=3D"faq-block__list-item embed-faq__item=
" data-toggle=3D"collapsed">
                <h2 class=3D"faq-block__question">What Is Latency and Ping?=
</h2>
                <i class=3D"faq-block__arrow down"></i>
                <div class=3D"faq-block__answer collapsed"><p>Latency and p=
ing refers to the =E2=80=9Clag=E2=80=9D on your connection. When you visit =
a website, all the data you see has to travel from a remote server to your =
computer. The amount of time it takes the request for that data to leave yo=
ur home, reach the server, and start returning data is called latency. Lear=
n the difference between <a href=3D"https://broadbandnow.com/guides/bandwid=
th-vs-latency">bandwidth and latency</a>.</p>
<hr>
<h3>Latency: the =E2=80=9CLong Distance Call=E2=80=9D Metaphor</h3>
<p>You can think of latency as the issue you get on a long-distance phone c=
all. Sometimes, you=E2=80=99ll hear your voice echoing a second after you s=
peak, or accidentally talk over somebody due to lag in hearing their voice.=
 =E2=80=9CLatency=E2=80=9D on an Internet connection is the same phenomenon=
 as =E2=80=9Clag=E2=80=9D on a long distance phone call, just with data rat=
her than voices.</p>
</div>
                              </li>
                          <li class=3D"faq-block__list-item embed-faq__item=
" data-toggle=3D"collapsed">
                <h2 class=3D"faq-block__question">How much bandwidth is eno=
ugh?</h2>
                <i class=3D"faq-block__arrow down"></i>
                <div class=3D"faq-block__answer collapsed"><p>The amount of=
 speed or bandwidth you need will vary widely depending on the size of your=
 household, number of users, intended activities, and etc. The best way to =
find out exactly how much bandwidth you need to subscribe to is to enter yo=
ur household details into the bandwidth calculator tool at the top of this =
page.</p>
</div>
                              </li>
                      </ul>
                      </div>
